node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Jennifer Tuffen on July 10, 2021 tagging @izkiz, and @izkizapp. May be an image of 1 person, flower and outdoors.

node.text:
…and they call it poppy love ❣️
Found the most beautiful poppy field on the South Downs a couple of weeks ago, we visited really early in the morning and apart from the birds, we had the whole red field to ourselves ☀️

From this spot on the South Downs you can see the sea, Portsmouth’s Spinnaker Tower & Chichester Cathedral 💒

Have you ever seen a poppy field? They can be hard to find as they very rarely pop up twice in the same place!

node.text: England, you’re such a babe when the sun is shining! 😍 I’m always happiest when on the beach splashing around, collecting shells or drinking wine on the sand 🙃🍷Are you a beach lover like me? ☀️👙⛱

user.full_name: Visit Saudi

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Jennifer Tuffen on June 13, 2021 tagging @visitsaudi. May be an image of one or more people, people standing and outdoors.

node.text:
AD I loved my time in Saudi with @VisitSaudi, especially watching the sunrise at Elephant Rock and exploring Hegra, an incredible Nabataean city that was built over 2000 years ago! As the world starts to open up and Saudi gets ready to host the amazing #SaudiSeasons later this year I look forward to being able to visit their beautiful country again! #VisitSaudi
#AlUla #Hegra #SaudiEvents #SaudiAdventure

node.text:
I love Spring in England when the woods turn a beautiful blue shade and it looks like a carpet on the forrest floor 💙 Here are 5 random facts about bluebells:

1) Over half the world’s populations of these iconic wildflowers grow in the UK. 
2) Bluebells are protected under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. If you dig up a wild bluebell you can be heavily fined! 
3) Ants help to spread bluebell seeds, so if you live near a bluebell wood you may find them popping up in your garden 🐜 
4) It takes several years for a native bluebell seed to grow into a bulb & subsequently flower. 
5) Folklore used to tell that bluebells ring at daybreak to call fairies to the woods. 🧚‍♀️
